<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Automated"><PMID Version="1">40675078</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2025</Year><Month>09</Month><Day>16</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2025</Year><Month>09</Month><Day>16</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1873-7072</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>492</Volume><Issue>Pt 2</Issue><PubDate><Year>2025</Year><Month>Nov</Month><Day>15</Day></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Food chemistry</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Food Chem</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Nanostructure-enhanced Raman spectroscopy for sensitive and on-site monitoring of anabolic-androgenic steroids in food and drug products.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>145535</StartPage><MedlinePgn>145535</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1016/j.foodchem.2025.145535</ELocationID><ELocationID EIdType="pii" ValidYN="Y">S0308-8146(25)02786-4</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText>The misuse of Anabolic-androgenic steroids (AAS) severely violates the principle of fair competition in sports and jeopardizes the physical and mental health of athlete. In this study, surface-enhanced Raman spectroscopy (SERS) was employed for the rapid detection of illicitly added AAS. Ag nanoflowers (Ag NFs) were used as substrates, and the addition of potassium iodide as a coagulant further enhanced the Raman signals. This approach effectively detected the characteristic peaks of four different AAS (clostebol, 4-chlorodehydromethyltestosterone, oxymetholone, and methandriol). The method exhibited high sensitivity and a wide dynamic range, enabling in situ detection of AAS illegally added to food and pharmaceutical products, with satisfactory recovery rates. The SERS-integrated analytical platform is capable of simultaneously monitoring illegal AAS additives in three critical matrices: aquatic environments, food systems, and pharmaceutical formulations. It enables on-site, portable operation and achieves a rapid response time of less than 70&#xa0;s.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>Copyright &#xa9; 2025 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Zhou</LastName><ForeName>Na</ForeName><Initials>N</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>School of Science, Xihua University, Chengdu 610039, PR China.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Zeng</LastName><ForeName>Yu</ForeName><Initials>Y</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>School of Science, Xihua University, Chengdu 610039, PR China.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Li</LastName><ForeName>Ting</ForeName><Initials>T</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>School of Science, Xihua University, Chengdu 610039, PR China.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Huang</LastName><ForeName>Qiuwen</ForeName><Initials>Q</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>School of Science, Xihua University, Chengdu 610039, PR China.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Chen</LastName><ForeName>Yushi</ForeName><Initials>Y</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>School of Science, Xihua University, Chengdu 610039, PR China.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Liu</LastName><ForeName>Siqing</ForeName><Initials>S</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>School of Science, Xihua University, Chengdu 610039, PR China.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Luo</LastName><ForeName>Xiaojun</ForeName><Initials>X</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>School of Science, Xihua University, Chengdu 610039, PR China; Asymmetric Synthesis and Chiral Technology Key Laboratory of Sichuan Province, Chengdu 610039, PR China. Electronic address: xajunluo@hotmail.com.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"